      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">GBP justifications, local relevance snippets</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local justifications</strong> are short text snippets that Google displays beneath a business listing in the Local Pack or Local Finder to explain why that result is relevant to the searcher's query. They are dynamically generated from multiple data sources — customer reviews, GBP services and products, website content, and in-store inventory data — and appear in formats like "Reviews mention: vegan options" or "Website mentions: emergency callouts."</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Location in SERP</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Below listing in Local Pack / Finder</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">CTR impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Positive — increases click probability</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local SEO work focuses on getting into the Local Pack. Local justifications are what makes your listing stand out once you're there. Two businesses at positions 1 and 2 can have very similar star ratings and review counts — justifications are often the differentiator that drives a click to one over the other.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are local justifications?</h2>
        <p>When Google displays a local business listing for a query, it sometimes adds a line of text beneath the listing's standard data (name, rating, category, address, hours). This extra line — the justification — gives the searcher a reason why this specific business matches their specific query.</p>
        <p>Justifications take several forms, each sourced from a different data point:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>"Reviews mention: [keyword]"</strong> — extracted from customer reviews that contain the searched term or a closely related term</li>
          <li><strong>"Website mentions: [keyword]"</strong> — pulled from the text of the business's website when it contains the search term</li>
          <li><strong>"Services: [keyword]"</strong> — sourced from the services section of the GBP listing</li>
          <li><strong>"Menu: [item]"</strong> — pulled from GBP menu data for restaurants and food businesses</li>
          <li><strong>"Products: [item]"</strong> — pulled from GBP products or local inventory ad feeds</li>
          <li><strong>"In stock nearby: [product]"</strong> — from LIA inventory data for retail businesses</li>
          <li><strong>"Posts: [topic]"</strong> — from recent GBP posts containing the searched keyword</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Google selects which justification to show (if any) based on what is most likely to be helpful to the specific searcher for the specific query. A search for "vegan pizza Denver" might show a review justification reading "Reviews mention: vegan-friendly crust" for a restaurant that has multiple such reviews, even if the business doesn't specifically target that keyword in their GBP description.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">When justifications appear</div>
          <p>Justifications are not shown for every listing or every query. Google displays them when: (1) the query is sufficiently specific to warrant extra relevance explanation, (2) the business has data that clearly matches the query, and (3) the justification text is concise enough to display cleanly within the SERP layout. More specific, long-tail local queries generate justifications more often than broad category queries.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why local justifications matter for local SEO</h2>
        <p>Justifications have both a direct and indirect impact on local search performance.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Increased click-through rate.</strong> A listing with a justification showing "Reviews mention: same-day service" for a query of "emergency plumber Denver" gives the searcher additional confidence before clicking. Studies from BrightLocal suggest listings with relevant justifications see 15-25% higher CTR than listings without them in competitive service categories.</li>
          <li><strong>Relevance signal reinforcement.</strong> Justifications are evidence that Google has found clear, consistent signals matching your business to the query. Consistently earning justifications for your core service keywords is a positive indicator of GBP and website data quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive differentiation within the Local Pack.</strong> When multiple businesses have similar star ratings and review counts, justifications provide a visible differentiation. A listing that shows "Reviews mention: child-friendly" for a dentist search targeting parents is meaningfully more persuasive than an identical listing without the justification.</li>
          <li><strong>Long-tail query coverage.</strong> Justifications appear most frequently for specific, long-tail local queries. They extend your visibility to queries you may not have explicitly optimised for, by surfacing relevant mentions buried in your reviews or GBP data.</li>
          <li><strong>Feedback loop for content strategy.</strong> The justifications Google surfaces tell you what aspects of your business searchers most frequently query. If "Reviews mention: fast turnaround" keeps appearing for your auto repair shop, it's a signal that speed of service is a differentiating factor worth amplifying in your marketing.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google generates local justifications</h2>
        <p>Google's justification algorithm works by matching query terms against the text it has indexed from multiple sources associated with your business. The process is:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Query analysis.</strong> Google identifies the key terms and entities in the search query — the service category, specific service variant, location, and any attribute modifiers (open late, pet-friendly, etc.).</li>
          <li><strong>Data source matching.</strong> Google scans all data sources linked to your GBP: reviews text, services section, products, menu, posts, website copy, and inventory feeds. It looks for the query terms or semantically close terms.</li>
          <li><strong>Justification selection.</strong> If a match is found, Google selects the most relevant and credible source. Review mentions are generally given highest trust weight, followed by website content, then GBP-direct data.</li>
          <li><strong>Display formatting.</strong> The justification is formatted into the standard phrase structure ("Reviews mention:", "Website mentions:", etc.) and displayed beneath the listing. Google keeps justifications to approximately 45-60 characters to fit cleanly within the listing layout.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="types">Types of local justifications — full breakdown</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Justification type</th><th>Source data</th><th>Format example</th><th>How to earn it</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Review justification</strong></td>
                <td>Customer review text</td>
                <td>"Reviews mention: emergency callouts"</td>
                <td>Encourage customers to mention specific services in reviews</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Website mention</strong></td>
                <td>Your website copy</td>
                <td>"Website mentions: same-day installation"</td>
                <td>Include specific service keywords on your website pages</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Services justification</strong></td>
                <td>GBP services section</td>
                <td>"Services: boiler repair"</td>
                <td>Add detailed services with keyword-rich descriptions in GBP</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Menu justification</strong></td>
                <td>GBP menu data</td>
                <td>"Menu: vegan options available"</td>
                <td>Build a complete GBP menu with dietary labels</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Products justification</strong></td>
                <td>GBP products / LIA feed</td>
                <td>"Products: iPhone 15 cases in stock"</td>
                <td>Add products to GBP or set up Local Inventory Ads</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>GBP post justification</strong></td>
                <td>Recent GBP post content</td>
                <td>"From the owner: now offering evening appointments"</td>
                <td>Publish weekly GBP posts including service keywords</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
