        <h2 id="examples">Real local justification examples</h2>
        <p>Here are four real search scenarios where justifications change which listing a searcher clicks.</p>

        <h3>1. Plumber — emergency service query</h3>
        <p>A searcher types "emergency plumber Denver." Three plumbers appear in the Local Pack. Two listings show standard data. The third shows "Reviews mention: available 24/7, fast response" — a review justification pulled from multiple customer reviews mentioning response time. The third listing gets 40% more clicks despite ranking third in the pack.</p>

        <h3>2. Restaurant — dietary restriction query</h3>
        <p>A searcher looks for "gluten-free pasta restaurant Chicago." Two Italian restaurants in the Local Pack. One shows a menu justification: "Menu: gluten-free pasta options." The other shows nothing. Click goes to the first — even though the second may also offer gluten-free options, it hasn't surfaced that data in its GBP menu.</p>

        <h3>3. Auto repair — specific service query</h3>
        <p>A searcher queries "brake pad replacement near me." A local auto shop's GBP services section lists "Brake pad replacement — same-day service for most vehicles." Google surfaces: "Services: brake pad replacement." The searcher sees a direct confirmation their specific need is offered and clicks through.</p>

        <h3>4. Salon — attribute query</h3>
        <p>A parent searches "kids haircut salon Austin." A salon with reviews mentioning "great with young children" and "patient with kids" earns the justification: "Reviews mention: great with children." Parents disproportionately click this listing even when it's positioned second in the pack.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local justifications vs rich snippets — what's the difference?</h2>
        <p>Both add extra information beneath a search result to increase click relevance, but they operate on different systems and different result types.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Local justifications</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Appear in the Local Pack and Local Finder</li>
              <li>Generated dynamically from GBP, reviews, website</li>
              <li>Cannot be directly controlled — only influenced</li>
              <li>Query-specific — change per search term</li>
              <li>Only shown for businesses with sufficient matching data</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Rich snippets (structured data)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Appear in organic search results</li>
              <li>Generated from schema.org markup you add to your site</li>
              <li>More directly controlled through structured data</li>
              <li>More stable — same format per page type</li>
              <li>Available to any page with valid schema markup</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices to earn local justifications</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Build your GBP services section with keyword-rich descriptions.</strong> Each service should have a name and description. The description is the primary source for services justifications. Write "Emergency boiler repair — same-day callouts in [city] area" not just "Boiler repair."</li>
          <li><strong>Coach customers to mention specific services in review requests.</strong> After a job, your review request can include a prompt: "If you're happy to leave a review, it helps others if you mention the specific service we helped with today." This drives review text that matches future queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish GBP posts weekly with service keywords.</strong> Posts are a live, fresh data source for Google. A weekly post about a specific service — "Now offering same-day fence installation in north Denver" — creates a post justification for related queries within hours of publishing.</li>
          <li><strong>Ensure your website mentions each service explicitly and naturally.</strong> Google pulls website mention justifications from your indexed pages. Each service page should mention the service name, location, and key differentiators in natural language in the first 200 words.</li>
          <li><strong>Add products and menus to GBP wherever applicable.</strong> For restaurants, fully build out the GBP menu including dietary labels (vegan, gluten-free, halal). For retail and service businesses, add GBP products for your top sellers. These are direct inputs to product and menu justifications.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor which justifications appear for your core keywords.</strong> Search for your primary service keywords in Google as an incognito user from your service area and record which justifications appear for your listing vs competitors. This reveals gaps in your data coverage.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to reviews that mention key services.</strong> Google may weight reviews you've acknowledged (via owner response) more heavily as credible signals. Responding also encourages more detailed follow-up reviews from satisfied customers.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — generic review requests</div>
          <p>Generic review requests ("Please leave us a 5-star review!") produce generic review text ("Great service, highly recommend!"). Generic review text doesn't trigger justifications. A request that says "Please mention the specific plumbing service we helped with today" produces reviews like "Fixed our emergency burst pipe on a Sunday morning, incredibly fast" — which directly matches high-intent emergency queries and earns a justification.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common local justification mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Leaving the GBP services section empty or with generic entries.</strong> "Plumbing services — we offer plumbing" generates no meaningful justification. Specific, keyword-rich service descriptions generate "Services: burst pipe emergency repair" justifications.</li>
          <li><strong>Not updating GBP posts after seasonal or service changes.</strong> Stale GBP posts with outdated service mentions or expired offers can generate misleading justifications. Keep posts current and remove or update offers that have expired.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming justifications are permanent.</strong> Justifications are dynamic and change based on query, user location, and GBP data freshness. A justification you see today may not appear tomorrow. Maintain all your data sources consistently to sustain justification eligibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-stuffing service descriptions with keywords.</strong> Google's NLP reads unnatural keyword density and may discount over-optimised GBP data. Write service descriptions that serve the reader first; the keyword signals will follow naturally.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the products section for retail businesses.</strong> The GBP products section is an underused source for product justifications. A hardware store that lists 50 specific products (drill bits, power tools, paint brands) earns product justifications for those specific product searches that competitors with empty product sections cannot match.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
